			<div id="content">
				<p>
					What is Linux? Linux is a class of operating systems; there are three main types of OSs for desktops: Microsoft Windows, Mac OS-X, and Linux. An operating system is a vival component to a computer, as it works in between programs and computer hardware. The choice of an OS matters because each is designed to operate differently. If multiple programs are running at the same time (as they usually are) and are asking for system resources like memory, CPU time, or access to the hard drive, how does it manage responding to those requests? How can the user interact with the computer? How can it quickly respond to user input? How are the files in the hard drive organized? How flexible and adjustable is the software? How is the computer secured against unauthorized or malicious actions? Does the user have access to the computer code that runs the operating system, and if so can they change it? An operating system has to provide solutions to all of these questions.
				</p>
				<p>
					Linux is the only class of operating systems that lets me use my computer however I want. I have complete flexibility over the control and functionality of my computer. I feel that this is how computers ought to work, and I'd go so far to say that it's my fundamental right. I want my computer to do a lot of things for me, but I still want to be able to adjust what it does if I so choose. Linux was designed with this in mind, and it's a completely free and open. There's a small amount of flexibility in Windows and OS-X, but not nearly as much as in Linux. I also want to be able to trust the stability, functionality, and security of my computer, and usually that involves having faith that Apple or Microsoft know what they're doing. I don't like this. I want to be able to confirm things for myself if I so choose, and I can do that thanks to the freedom of open-source software. This is why in the fall of 2012 I switched from Microsoft Windows in Linux Mint.
				</p>
				<p>
					I found a fantastic article titled "10 fundamental differences between Linux and Windows". It's very informative, and I recommend you check it out: <a href="http://www.techrepublic.com/blog/10things/10-fundamental-differences-between-linux-and-windows/406">article on TechRepublic.com</a>
				</p>
				<p>
					I think many people consider Linux to be really technical, and they aren't interested because they are happy with their setup in Windows or OS-X. This is unfortunate, and I wish people would do some research and educate themselves a bit more. I like being informed when I made a decision, and my choice of operating systems is no different. I don't have the time or desire to custom-compile stuff in the command-line; I like to click on things just like most people do. I can do this in Linux Mint, which is really nice.
				</p>
