				<p>
					There are many different "distributions" of Linux. Ubuntu, Mint, Redhat, and Fedora are but a few. Each distribution is still Linux and have a lot in common, but they each approach problems a bit differently. For example, some focus their software to be on the cutting-edge at the risk of instability, others are more conservative and use software that is throughly tested and very stable. Linux Mint takes this latter approach, which I appreciate. There are some pretty cool websites out there for helping newcomers choose a distribution that's right for them. I've used <a href="http://www.zegeniestudios.net/ldc/index.php?lang=en">the one on ZegenieStudios.net</a> as well as <a href="http://www.linux-chooser.com/">linux-chooser.com</a> and they both recommend Linux Mint to me.
				<p>
					Agreeing with <a href="http://www.linuxmint.com/about.php">the reasons on LinuxMint.com</a>, I like Linux Mint because:
					<ul>
						<li>
							It's is designed to be a modern, elegant and comfortable operating system which is both powerful and easy to use.
						</li>
						<li>
							It's is now the 4th most widely used home operating system behind Microsoft Windows, Apple Mac OS and Canonical's Ubuntu. This means that there is a wide user base and a significant level of community support.
						</li>
						<li>
							It works out of the box, with full multimedia support and is extremely easy to use.
						</li>
						<li>
							It's both free of cost and open source. I can donate to the team to support them if I want.
						</li>
						<li>
							It's community-driven. Users are encouraged to send feedback to the project so that their ideas can be used to improve Linux Mint. Brilliant, right!
						</li>
						<li>
							Multiple desktops to choose from. Windows forces you to use a particular set of buttons, colors, and menus indicative to that version of Windows. Windows XP's look and controls are much different than Window 7's. If I don't like Mint's default controls, I can switch to a different "desktop". Cinnamon, KDE, MATE, and Xfce are some of the most common desktops to choose from.
						<li>
							Linux Mint has one of the best software managers, and it maintains a list of over 41,000 software packages. I can choose a program from this list and install it without even going to the Internet. This is a <b>huge</b> security improvement over download software from sketchy websites that you have trust. Linux Mint's package list is based on Debian and Ubuntu, so there's a lot of compatibility too.
						</li>
						<li>
							It's safe and reliable. Thanks to a conservative approach to software updates, a unique Update Manager and the robustness of its Linux architecture, Linux Mint is secure and requires very little maintenance (no regressions, no antivirus, no anti-spyware... etc). Wouldn't it be nice if you could update everything in one place? It's called the Update Manager.
						</li>
					</ul>
				</p>
				<p>
					Linux Mint is just brilliant in so many ways. When my computer boots up, I get this feeling of freedom, security, brilliance, and control that I don't feel anywhere else. I'm intrigued enough to keep digging into the technical details of how it works, and it's so cool that I don't have to worry about tiptoeing around the legalities of proprietary software. It's all open source and brilliant! :)
